1
00:00:03,320 --> 00:00:05,480
-Take a punt.
-CLARA: Right.

2
00:00:05,800 --> 00:00:08,120
Your choice. Wherever, whenever,

3
00:00:08,600 --> 00:00:11,240
anywhere in time and space.

4
00:00:11,760 --> 00:00:14,920
Well, there is something,

5
00:00:15,000 --> 00:00:18,480
someone that I've always wanted to meet.

6
00:00:18,560 --> 00:00:20,120
-But I know what you'll say.
-Try me.

7
00:00:20,200 --> 00:00:22,960
You'll say he's made-up,
that there is no such thing.

8
00:00:23,040 --> 00:00:24,640
-Go on.
-It's...

9
00:00:26,920 --> 00:00:28,200
It's Robin Hood.

10
00:00:28,560 --> 00:00:30,120
-Robin Hood.
-Yeah!

11
00:00:30,480 --> 00:00:33,760
I love that story. I've always loved it,
ever since I was little...

12
00:00:33,840 --> 00:00:36,760
Robin Hood, the heroic outlaw

13
00:00:36,960 --> 00:00:38,520
who robs from the rich
and gives to the poor.

14
00:00:38,600 --> 00:00:39,600
(CHUCKLES) Yeah!

15
00:00:39,680 --> 00:00:41,080
He's made-up. There's no such thing.

16
00:00:41,160 --> 00:00:42,600
Ah, you see?

17
00:00:43,680 --> 00:00:47,480
Old-fashioned heroes only exist
in old-fashioned storybooks, Clara.

18
00:00:47,680 --> 00:00:48,960
And what about you?

19
00:00:49,480 --> 00:00:50,480
Me?

20
00:00:50,560 --> 00:00:52,080
Yeah, you.

21
00:00:52,400 --> 00:00:54,680
You stop bad things happening
every minute of every day,

22
00:00:54,760 --> 00:00:57,200
that sounds pretty heroic to me.

23
00:00:59,120 --> 00:01:01,720
Just passing the time.
Hey, what about Mars?

24
00:01:01,800 --> 00:01:03,840
-What?
-The Ice Warrior hives!

25
00:01:03,920 --> 00:01:04,960
You said it was my choice.

26
00:01:05,040 --> 00:01:07,720
Or the Tumescent Arrows
of the Half-Light!

27
00:01:07,920 --> 00:01:09,520
-Those girls can hold their drink!
-Doctor...

28
00:01:09,600 --> 00:01:13,080
And fracture 15 different levels
of reality simultaneously.

29
00:01:13,440 --> 00:01:15,800
-I think I've got a Polaroid somewhere.
-Doctor!

30
00:01:16,160 --> 00:01:18,920
My choice. Robin Hood. Show me.

31
00:01:19,880 --> 00:01:21,280
Very well.

32
00:01:24,680 --> 00:01:25,680
(CLEARS THROAT)

33
00:01:27,120 --> 00:01:29,240
Earth. England.

34
00:01:30,480 --> 00:01:32,480
Sherwood Forest.

35
00:01:32,680 --> 00:01:35,400
1190 AD...

36
00:01:35,680 --> 00:01:37,600
- (CLICKS BUTTON)
-...ish.

37
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:39,560
But you'll only be disappointed.

38
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:42,120
(WHOOSHING)

39
00:02:04,040 --> 00:02:07,400
No damsels in distress,
no pretty castles,

40
00:02:07,480 --> 00:02:09,840
no such thing as Robin Hood.

41
00:02:18,960 --> 00:02:20,160
ROBIN: You called?

42
00:02:21,200 --> 00:02:22,960
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

43
00:02:59,040 --> 00:03:02,120
Very, very nicely done
with the box, sir.

44
00:03:02,320 --> 00:03:07,480
I saw a Turk perform something
very similar at Nottingham Fayre.

45
00:03:08,080 --> 00:03:11,320
It's a trick with mirrors, no doubt?

46
00:03:11,600 --> 00:03:14,800
-A trick?
-A... A good jest. Ha-ha!

47
00:03:15,400 --> 00:03:17,520
This is not a trick, this is a Tardis.

48
00:03:17,600 --> 00:03:22,000
Whatever it is, you bony rascal,
I'm afraid I must relieve you of it.

49
00:03:22,200 --> 00:03:25,240
It's my property, that's what it is.

50
00:03:25,840 --> 00:03:29,800
Well, don't you know all property
is theft to Robin Hood?

51
00:03:29,880 --> 00:03:30,960
You're not serious.

52
00:03:31,040 --> 00:03:33,560
I'm many things, sir,
but I'm never that.

53
00:03:33,840 --> 00:03:35,680
Robin Hood laughs in the face of all.

54
00:03:36,160 --> 00:03:37,480
Ha-ha-ha!

55
00:03:37,960 --> 00:03:40,400
And do people ever punch you
in the face when you do that?

56
00:03:40,480 --> 00:03:43,000
-Not as yet.
-Lucky I'm here then, isn't it?

57
00:03:43,080 --> 00:03:46,560
Might be a...a little bit much

58
00:03:46,680 --> 00:03:49,680
but whoo! What do you reckon, Doctor?

59
00:03:51,280 --> 00:03:53,240
By all the saints!

60
00:03:54,880 --> 00:03:56,800
Are there any more in there?

61
00:03:56,880 --> 00:03:58,280
-Is that...
-No.

62
00:03:59,200 --> 00:04:00,520
Oh, my God!

63
00:04:02,720 --> 00:04:04,240
Oh, my God! It is, isn't it?

64
00:04:04,320 --> 00:04:07,200
Oh, you found him.
You actually found Robin Hood.

65
00:04:07,360 --> 00:04:09,360
That is not Robin Hood.

66
00:04:09,440 --> 00:04:14,680
Well, then who, sir, is about
to relieve you of your magic box?

67
00:04:19,280 --> 00:04:21,200
Nobody, sir.

68
00:04:21,440 --> 00:04:22,840
Not in this universe or the next.

69
00:04:22,960 --> 00:04:24,560
Well, then draw your sword
and prove your words.

70
00:04:24,640 --> 00:04:25,640
I have no sword.

71
00:04:26,840 --> 00:04:28,640
I don't need a sword.

72
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:30,880
Because I am the Doctor.

73
00:04:31,920 --> 00:04:34,560
And this is my spoon!

74
00:04:34,960 --> 00:04:36,080
En garde!

75
00:04:39,000 --> 00:04:40,320
(GRUNTS)

76
00:04:45,840 --> 00:04:47,880
(GRUNTING)

77
00:04:52,760 --> 00:04:53,840
Ow!

78
00:04:53,920 --> 00:04:56,200
-You're amazing!
-DOCTOR: I've had some experience.

79
00:04:56,280 --> 00:04:57,360
Richard the Lionheart!

80
00:04:57,880 --> 00:04:59,320
Cyrano de Bergerac!

81
00:04:59,400 --> 00:05:01,800
Errol Flynn! He had the most enormous...

82
00:05:01,880 --> 00:05:04,000
-(CLEARS THROAT)
-...ego!

83
00:05:04,080 --> 00:05:05,240
Takes one to know one.

84
00:05:06,240 --> 00:05:08,040
Oh...you!

85
00:05:23,600 --> 00:05:24,600
(GRUNTS)

86
00:05:26,440 --> 00:05:27,560
Doctor!

87
00:05:29,720 --> 00:05:31,680
Like I said,

88
00:05:31,760 --> 00:05:33,000
my box.

89
00:05:34,560 --> 00:05:35,840
Doctor?

90
00:05:38,880 --> 00:05:39,880
Ahh!

91
00:05:51,760 --> 00:05:53,680
In the name of all that's holy,

92
00:05:53,800 --> 00:05:57,920
take our money, take our treasure,
but spare my ward!

93
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:01,280
-Do not fuss, all will be well.
-This is the Sheriff's doing!

94
00:06:01,360 --> 00:06:04,560
If he were here now,
I'd tear out his black heart!

95
00:06:04,640 --> 00:06:05,760
Would you, now?

96
00:06:08,040 --> 00:06:09,040
(GIRL SCREAMING)

97
00:06:09,280 --> 00:06:14,480
Or are you as milk-live red as your
name suggests, Master Quayle?

98
00:06:14,840 --> 00:06:17,600
QUAYLE: Take me! Spare this dear child!

99
00:06:17,680 --> 00:06:18,880
Take you?

100
00:06:19,480 --> 00:06:21,600
A lardy lack-wit like you?

101
00:06:22,600 --> 00:06:25,040
It's lab our we require up at the castle.

102
00:06:25,120 --> 00:06:28,720
Labour and gold, not old men
and their worthless baubles.

103
00:06:28,920 --> 00:06:32,040
This will be a great help,
Master Quayle, believe me.

104
00:06:32,520 --> 00:06:34,320
Newcomer to Sherwood, are we?

105
00:06:34,680 --> 00:06:35,720
Yes, my lord.

106
00:06:35,920 --> 00:06:38,280
You may also prove useful. Bring her.

107
00:06:39,360 --> 00:06:41,600
QUAYLE: Your days are numbered, you cur!

108
00:06:49,240 --> 00:06:51,080
You shall live to regret that.

109
00:06:51,320 --> 00:06:54,440
Actually, no.

110
00:06:56,160 --> 00:06:57,720
-You won't.
-(GRUNTS)

111
00:06:57,880 --> 00:06:58,880
No!

112
00:07:00,000 --> 00:07:02,000
No! (SOBBING)

113
00:07:12,640 --> 00:07:14,240
Let me introduce you to my men.

114
00:07:14,840 --> 00:07:17,360
This is Will Scarlett.

115
00:07:17,480 --> 00:07:21,160
He is a cheeky rogue with a good
sword arm and a slippery tongue.

116
00:07:21,320 --> 00:07:22,840
My lady.

117
00:07:22,920 --> 00:07:25,680
Argh! What do you want with my hair?

118
00:07:25,880 --> 00:07:27,600
Well, it's realistic,
I'll give you that.

119
00:07:28,080 --> 00:07:30,080
And this is Friar Tuck.

120
00:07:30,200 --> 00:07:32,880
Aptly named for the amount of grub
he tucks into!

121
00:07:32,960 --> 00:07:35,200
You skinny blackguard!

122
00:07:35,440 --> 00:07:38,400
-Ooh! What are you doing?
-This isn't a real sandal!

123
00:07:38,480 --> 00:07:39,480
Yes, it is.

124
00:07:39,560 --> 00:07:40,800
Oh, yes, it is.

125
00:07:41,440 --> 00:07:45,720
This, uh, is Alan-a-Dale.
He's a master of the lute,

126
00:07:46,080 --> 00:07:48,320
whose music brightens up
these dark days.

127
00:07:48,480 --> 00:07:50,640
# The stranger you are welcome here

128
00:07:50,920 --> 00:07:52,800
# In Sherwood's bonny glade... #

129
00:07:52,880 --> 00:07:54,000
ow!

130
00:07:54,160 --> 00:07:56,520
Sorry, sorry. Blood analysis.

131
00:07:58,200 --> 00:08:00,280
Oh! All those diseases!

132
00:08:01,240 --> 00:08:03,600
If you were real,
you'd be dead in six months.

133
00:08:03,680 --> 00:08:05,080
I am real.

134
00:08:05,400 --> 00:08:06,520
Bye.

135
00:08:06,760 --> 00:08:10,320
And this is John Little.

136
00:08:10,440 --> 00:08:11,920
Called Little John.

137
00:08:12,480 --> 00:08:16,200
He's my loyal companion
in many an adventure.

138
00:08:16,360 --> 00:08:17,600
-Oh!
-(LAUGHING)

139
00:08:17,680 --> 00:08:18,880
Works every time!

140
00:08:22,680 --> 00:08:24,120
Oh, I cannot believe this!

141
00:08:24,200 --> 00:08:29,000
You... You really are Robin Hood
and his Merry Men!

142
00:08:29,280 --> 00:08:31,520
Aye! That is an apt description.

143
00:08:31,680 --> 00:08:34,600
-Ha! What say you, lads?
-ALL: Aye!

144
00:08:34,960 --> 00:08:36,960
Stop laughing!

145
00:08:38,200 --> 00:08:39,960
Why are you always doing that?

146
00:08:40,120 --> 00:08:42,200
Are you all simple or something?

147
00:08:44,680 --> 00:08:46,160
-I'm going to need a sample.
-Of what?

148
00:08:46,240 --> 00:08:47,520
(CLARA CLEARS THROAT)

149
00:08:47,680 --> 00:08:49,280
Excuse me. Sorry.

150
00:08:49,560 --> 00:08:51,120
(CLEARS THROAT) What are you doing?

151
00:08:51,200 --> 00:08:53,240
Well, they're not holograms,
that much is obvious.

152
00:08:53,320 --> 00:08:55,120
Could be a theme park from the future.

153
00:08:55,800 --> 00:08:58,200
-Or we might be inside a miniscope.
-Oh, shut up.

154
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:01,120
A miniscope! Yes, of course! Why not?

155
00:09:03,440 --> 00:09:08,040
Your friend seems not quite
of the real world.

156
00:09:08,160 --> 00:09:11,320
No. No, he's not, really,
not most of the time.

157
00:09:12,160 --> 00:09:13,320
Dark days?

158
00:09:14,040 --> 00:09:15,040
My lady?

159
00:09:15,120 --> 00:09:17,600
You said that these were dark days,
what did you mean?

160
00:09:17,960 --> 00:09:20,280
King Richard is away on crusade,
my lady.

161
00:09:20,360 --> 00:09:22,280
His tyrant of a brother rules instead.

162
00:09:22,680 --> 00:09:24,720
And the sheriff?
'Cause there is a sheriff, right?

163
00:09:24,840 --> 00:09:27,840
Aye. It is indeed this jackal
of the princes

164
00:09:27,920 --> 00:09:29,640
who seeks to oppress us for evermore.

165
00:09:29,720 --> 00:09:32,240
Or six months, in your case.

166
00:09:32,800 --> 00:09:35,800
It is a shame to dwell on murky thoughts

167
00:09:37,040 --> 00:09:39,040
when there is such beauty here.

168
00:09:42,600 --> 00:09:43,960
Why are you so sad?

169
00:09:47,320 --> 00:09:48,640
Why do you think me sad?

170
00:09:49,840 --> 00:09:52,600
Because the Doctor's right.
You laugh too much.

171
00:09:54,240 --> 00:09:56,840
You know, I do not live this outlaw life
by choice.

172
00:09:57,320 --> 00:09:59,920
You see before you Robert...

173
00:10:00,000 --> 00:10:01,560
-Earl of Lox...
-Earl of Loxley.

174
00:10:01,640 --> 00:10:02,920
-...ley.
-Yes.

175
00:10:03,680 --> 00:10:05,320
Sorry, do go on.

176
00:10:06,840 --> 00:10:08,120
I, um...

177
00:10:09,040 --> 00:10:11,040
I had my lands and titles
stripped from me.

178
00:10:11,840 --> 00:10:14,320
I dared to speak out
against Prince John.

179
00:10:14,400 --> 00:10:17,200
But I lost the thing most dear to me.

180
00:10:18,560 --> 00:10:19,760
What was she called?

181
00:10:22,320 --> 00:10:23,760
You're so very quick.

182
00:10:24,480 --> 00:10:27,560
-How does the Doctor stand it?
-Marian?

183
00:10:28,280 --> 00:10:30,800
-You know her?
-Oh, yes.

184
00:10:31,480 --> 00:10:32,920
I have always known her.

185
00:10:33,040 --> 00:10:37,680
It was Marian who told me that
I must stand up and be counted.

186
00:10:39,840 --> 00:10:43,440
But I was afraid.

187
00:10:44,840 --> 00:10:48,080
Now this green canopy is my palace

188
00:10:48,960 --> 00:10:50,880
and the rough ground my feather bed.

189
00:10:51,200 --> 00:10:53,880
And maybe one day I will return home
but until that day...

190
00:10:54,080 --> 00:10:56,200
Until that day, it is beholden on me

191
00:10:56,440 --> 00:10:58,720
to be the man Marian wanted,

192
00:10:59,200 --> 00:11:02,800
to be a hero for those
this tyrant sheriff slaughters.

193
00:11:03,080 --> 00:11:04,640
What time is it, Mr Hood?

194
00:11:05,960 --> 00:11:07,440
Ah, somewhat after noon.

195
00:11:08,040 --> 00:11:11,160
No, no. Time of year. What season?

196
00:11:11,680 --> 00:11:15,040
Oh, Dame Autumn has draped her
mellow skirts about the forest, Doctor.

197
00:11:15,120 --> 00:11:17,040
The time of mists
and harvest approaches...

198
00:11:17,120 --> 00:11:20,360
Yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah. All very poetic.

199
00:11:20,800 --> 00:11:22,960
But it's very green hereabouts,
though, isn't it?

200
00:11:23,040 --> 00:11:25,480
And like I said, very sunny.

201
00:11:25,560 --> 00:11:28,200
-So?
-Have you been to Nottingham?

202
00:11:30,200 --> 00:11:31,600
Climate change?

203
00:11:31,680 --> 00:11:32,960
It's 1190.

204
00:11:33,200 --> 00:11:34,440
You must excuse me.

205
00:11:34,880 --> 00:11:37,600
The Sheriff has issued a proclamation

206
00:11:37,960 --> 00:11:41,520
and tomorrow there is to be a contest

207
00:11:41,760 --> 00:11:43,920
to find the best archer in the land.

208
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:47,560
And the bounty...
It's an arrow made of pure gold.

209
00:11:47,640 --> 00:11:49,440
No! Don't... Don't go! It's a trap.

210
00:11:49,520 --> 00:11:51,200
Well, of course it is!

211
00:11:51,360 --> 00:11:54,440
But a contest to find the best
archer in the land?

212
00:11:55,600 --> 00:11:56,960
There is no contest.

213
00:11:57,080 --> 00:11:59,120
(ALL LAUGHING LOUDLY)

214
00:12:00,120 --> 00:12:02,200
Right, that isn't even funny.

215
00:12:02,800 --> 00:12:04,360
That was bantering.

216
00:12:04,560 --> 00:12:07,000
I am totally against bantering.

217
00:12:09,120 --> 00:12:11,560
How can you be so sure
he's not the real thing?

218
00:12:11,640 --> 00:12:13,480
Because he can't be.

219
00:12:13,920 --> 00:12:16,760
When did you stop
believing in everything?

220
00:12:16,840 --> 00:12:19,800
When did you start believing in
impossible heroes?

221
00:12:21,920 --> 00:12:23,440
Don't you know?

222
00:12:27,520 --> 00:12:29,520
In a way, it's rather sweet.

223
00:12:34,920 --> 00:12:36,480
(SCANNER HUMMING)

224
00:12:52,040 --> 00:12:56,680
In the contest for the golden arrow,

225
00:12:57,080 --> 00:13:01,040
after 10 rounds, the battle is betwixt

226
00:13:01,120 --> 00:13:03,320
our lord Sheriff...

227
00:13:03,400 --> 00:13:04,560
(CROWD CHEERING)

228
00:13:05,360 --> 00:13:09,800
...and the stranger
known as Tom the Tinker!

229
00:13:09,920 --> 00:13:10,920
(CROWD CHEERING)

230
00:13:12,320 --> 00:13:15,320
Perhaps not such a stranger after all.

231
00:13:15,680 --> 00:13:17,320
HERALD: Take your places!

232
00:13:25,920 --> 00:13:29,960
Shall we make the contest
a little more interesting, my lord?

233
00:13:30,280 --> 00:13:32,240
The targets seem a little close.
What say you?

234
00:13:32,320 --> 00:13:33,560
Another 20 paces?

235
00:13:33,920 --> 00:13:35,200
Why not?

236
00:13:38,080 --> 00:13:39,520
(CROWD SHOUTING ENCOURAGEMENT)

237
00:13:51,440 --> 00:13:52,600
(CROWD GASPS)

238
00:13:54,000 --> 00:13:58,800
Now, Tinker. Let us see thy true face.

239
00:14:07,440 --> 00:14:08,440
Whoo!

240
00:14:09,640 --> 00:14:13,400
HERALD: Ye gads! He has split the arrow!

241
00:14:13,480 --> 00:14:18,000
Truly, he is the finest archer
in all England!

242
00:14:18,520 --> 00:14:23,080
Come forward, Tinker,
and claim your prize.

243
00:14:23,200 --> 00:14:24,840
(CROWD CHEERING AND APPLAUDING)

244
00:14:26,400 --> 00:14:27,400
(CROWD GASPS)

245
00:14:30,200 --> 00:14:31,320
(CROWD APPLAUDING)

246
00:14:32,480 --> 00:14:34,520
He's full of surprises, isn't he?

247
00:14:34,920 --> 00:14:35,920
I'm the Doctor.

248
00:14:36,520 --> 00:14:38,920
My skills as a bowman
speak for themselves.

249
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:40,800
I claim my reward.

250
00:14:44,360 --> 00:14:45,680
A mere bauble.

251
00:14:46,720 --> 00:14:47,840
(CROWD EXCLAIMING)

252
00:14:49,120 --> 00:14:51,720
-I want something else.
-Name it.

253
00:14:52,000 --> 00:14:53,000
Enlightenment.

254
00:15:12,080 --> 00:15:14,480
This is getting silly.

255
00:15:14,640 --> 00:15:15,640
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER HUMMING)

256
00:15:21,160 --> 00:15:23,680
Fascinating. Seize him!

257
00:15:26,960 --> 00:15:28,040
Ahhh!

258
00:15:28,120 --> 00:15:29,400
What are you doing? Put that down!

259
00:15:29,480 --> 00:15:31,840
I'm fine! I take Year 7
for after-school tae Kwon do.

260
00:15:31,920 --> 00:15:33,320
Don't worry, Doctor! I'll save you!

261
00:15:33,400 --> 00:15:35,040
-I don't need saving!
-Your honour is safe.

262
00:15:35,120 --> 00:15:37,320
-I know!
-For I am Robin!

263
00:15:37,600 --> 00:15:40,640
-ALL: Hooray!
-Robin Hood!

264
00:15:41,480 --> 00:15:42,680
(CHEERING)

265
00:15:46,000 --> 00:15:47,000
(CROWD GASPS)

266
00:15:53,280 --> 00:15:54,280
Robot!

267
00:15:58,520 --> 00:15:59,800
Now we're getting somewhere!

268
00:16:00,520 --> 00:16:01,640
Take them!

269
00:16:02,280 --> 00:16:03,360
Kill the rest!

270
00:16:05,360 --> 00:16:06,680
SHERIFF: Kill them all!

271
00:16:06,760 --> 00:16:07,800
(CROWD SCREAMING)

272
00:16:15,760 --> 00:16:17,320
-He surrenders!
-What?

273
00:16:17,400 --> 00:16:18,560
Hail!

274
00:16:18,640 --> 00:16:20,760
ROBIN: You miserable cur!
I had them on the run!

275
00:16:20,840 --> 00:16:24,000
Flee, lads, flee!
Live to fight another day!

276
00:16:24,960 --> 00:16:25,960
Come on!

277
00:16:26,600 --> 00:16:29,440
To the dungeons with all of them!

278
00:16:29,720 --> 00:16:30,800
What are you up to?

279
00:16:30,880 --> 00:16:32,480
Quickest way to find out
anybody's plans.

280
00:16:32,600 --> 00:16:34,360
Get yourself captured.

281
00:16:38,400 --> 00:16:40,960
(PEOPLE CRYING OUT)

282
00:16:43,840 --> 00:16:44,840
(GROANING)

283
00:16:51,760 --> 00:16:53,560
Here, let me help you.

284
00:16:53,960 --> 00:16:56,760
Thank you, lady.

285
00:17:01,960 --> 00:17:05,320
What are you? Gargoyle, what are you?

286
00:17:05,440 --> 00:17:06,520
Leave It.

287
00:17:06,600 --> 00:17:09,360
He only needs to rest.
We all need to rest.

288
00:17:09,520 --> 00:17:13,480
Analysis shows
that peasant creature is spent.

289
00:17:13,680 --> 00:17:15,240
No, no. Please.

290
00:17:15,320 --> 00:17:17,800
Usefulness expired.

291
00:17:17,920 --> 00:17:19,800
No. No!

292
00:17:20,040 --> 00:17:21,120
No!

293
00:17:26,920 --> 00:17:28,000
Damn you!

294
00:17:30,160 --> 00:17:32,160
Damn you and that villain the Sheriff!

295
00:17:36,240 --> 00:17:37,600
(SOBBING)

296
00:17:39,400 --> 00:17:42,080
Splendid! Enchained!

297
00:17:42,160 --> 00:17:43,200
Yep.

298
00:17:43,280 --> 00:17:45,200
Trussed up like turkey-cocks!

299
00:17:45,880 --> 00:17:47,280
Thanks to your friend.

300
00:17:47,400 --> 00:17:49,000
Shut it, Hoodie.

301
00:17:49,680 --> 00:17:51,000
I saved your life.

302
00:17:51,120 --> 00:17:52,840
I had the situation well in hand.

303
00:17:53,160 --> 00:17:55,440
Long-haired ninny versus
robot killer knights?

304
00:17:55,800 --> 00:17:56,880
I know where I'd put my money.

305
00:17:56,960 --> 00:18:00,040
If you had not betrayed me,
I would have been triumphant.

306
00:18:00,240 --> 00:18:02,560
You would have been a little
puff of smoke and ashes!

307
00:18:02,680 --> 00:18:04,040
-Ha!
-You'd have been floating around

308
00:18:04,120 --> 00:18:07,160
in tiny little laughing bits
in people's goblets.

309
00:18:07,240 --> 00:18:08,440
Balderdash! Ha!

310
00:18:08,520 --> 00:18:10,760
Oh, right, here we go,
it's laughing time!

311
00:18:11,280 --> 00:18:13,840
Well, you amuse me, grey old man!

312
00:18:13,920 --> 00:18:16,400
Guard! He's laughing again!

313
00:18:16,480 --> 00:18:18,480
You can't keep me locked up
with a laughing person!

314
00:18:18,560 --> 00:18:20,440
Oh, I find that...
I find that quite funny.

315
00:18:20,520 --> 00:18:24,240
Do you know, I feel another laugh
coming on. Aha-ha-ha!

316
00:18:24,320 --> 00:18:27,360
Guard, I cannot remain in this cell!

317
00:18:27,560 --> 00:18:29,880
-Execute me now!
-You heard him. Execute the old fool!

318
00:18:29,960 --> 00:18:31,520
No, no, hang on, execute him!

319
00:18:31,600 --> 00:18:33,560
I do not fear death, so execute away!

320
00:18:33,640 --> 00:18:36,040
Execute him! I'd like to see if his head
keeps laughing

321
00:18:36,120 --> 00:18:37,200
when you chop it off!

322
00:18:37,280 --> 00:18:39,760
Oh, Robin Hood always laughs
in the face of death.

323
00:18:39,840 --> 00:18:41,840
Yes, rolling around the floor laughing,

324
00:18:41,920 --> 00:18:43,520
I would pay good money to see that!

325
00:18:43,600 --> 00:18:44,840
-Guard!
-Guard!

326
00:18:44,920 --> 00:18:45,960
-Guard!
-Guard!

327
00:18:46,040 --> 00:18:47,040
-Guard!
-Guard!

328
00:18:47,120 --> 00:18:48,840
Will you two shut up!

329
00:18:55,160 --> 00:18:59,480
Do either of you understand
in any way at all

330
00:19:01,440 --> 00:19:04,080
that there isn't actually
a guard out there?

331
00:19:08,840 --> 00:19:09,880
Oh.

332
00:19:10,040 --> 00:19:11,040
I did, in fact.

333
00:19:11,120 --> 00:19:12,240
No, you didn't.

334
00:19:12,320 --> 00:19:13,680
I said shut up.

335
00:19:13,760 --> 00:19:15,920
The Doctor and Robin Hood
locked up in a cellar.

336
00:19:16,000 --> 00:19:17,440
Is this seriously the best
that you can do?

337
00:19:17,680 --> 00:19:20,280
You're determined to starve to death
in here, squabbling.

338
00:19:21,360 --> 00:19:22,960
Well, I'll tell you one thing.

339
00:19:23,560 --> 00:19:26,320
I'd last a lot longer
than this desiccated man-crone.

340
00:19:26,400 --> 00:19:27,400
(SNIGGERS)

341
00:19:28,880 --> 00:19:30,400
-Really?
-Really.

342
00:19:30,680 --> 00:19:33,000
Well, you know what?

343
00:19:33,760 --> 00:19:36,880
I think you'll find
I have a certain genetic advantage. Oh!

344
00:19:36,960 --> 00:19:39,520
-Oh!
-It is not a competition

345
00:19:39,600 --> 00:19:40,800
about who can die slower.

346
00:19:40,880 --> 00:19:43,000
It would definitely be me,
though, wouldn't it?

347
00:19:43,200 --> 00:19:45,360
There was supposed to be a plan.
Do either of you two have a plan?

348
00:19:45,440 --> 00:19:46,880
Yeah, of course I have a plan.

349
00:19:46,960 --> 00:19:48,080
I, too, have a plan.

350
00:19:48,160 --> 00:19:49,560
Okay, Robin, you first.

351
00:19:50,160 --> 00:19:51,720
-Why him?
-Doctor, shut up.

352
00:19:51,800 --> 00:19:53,560
Robin, your plan.

353
00:19:56,000 --> 00:19:57,080
I am...

354
00:19:58,800 --> 00:20:00,440
biding my time.

355
00:20:01,880 --> 00:20:04,920
Thank you, Prince of Thieves.
Last of the Time Lords?

356
00:20:05,400 --> 00:20:07,640
Yes, I have a plan.

357
00:20:07,880 --> 00:20:11,120
Can you explain your plan without using
the word "sonic screwdriver"?

358
00:20:12,440 --> 00:20:14,800
Because you might have forgotten
the Sheriff of Nottingham

359
00:20:14,880 --> 00:20:16,560
has taken your screwdriver, just saying.

360
00:20:16,640 --> 00:20:17,680
It's always the screwdriver.

361
00:20:17,760 --> 00:20:19,680
Okay, well,
let's hear Robin's plan first.

362
00:20:19,840 --> 00:20:21,760
-For God's sake!
-(DOOR OPENING)

363
00:20:21,920 --> 00:20:23,680
See? There was a guard.

364
00:20:23,760 --> 00:20:26,280
There was guard listening
the whole time, I knew it.

365
00:20:26,400 --> 00:20:28,320
Ha-ha-ha-ha!

366
00:20:29,520 --> 00:20:32,280
The Sheriff himself
commanded me to listen,

367
00:20:32,360 --> 00:20:35,200
to find out which of you
is the true ringleader.

368
00:20:35,680 --> 00:20:39,240
Ah, so he can do the interrogating.
Very wise.

369
00:20:39,360 --> 00:20:41,240
Excellent. He will get nothing from me!

370
00:20:41,320 --> 00:20:43,800
No, no, no. He will get nothing from me,

371
00:20:43,880 --> 00:20:46,760
because interrogation, that's where
I always turn the tables.

372
00:20:46,840 --> 00:20:48,200
You see, that's my plan.

373
00:20:48,280 --> 00:20:49,720
Just hurry up and take me to him.

374
00:20:49,800 --> 00:20:51,640
No, no, chop-chop, come on!

375
00:20:54,880 --> 00:20:56,280
-Seriously?
-Come on.

376
00:20:56,360 --> 00:20:57,360
No.

377
00:20:57,440 --> 00:20:58,480
ROBIN: What are you doing?

378
00:20:58,560 --> 00:21:00,160
Don't be ridiculous!

379
00:21:00,880 --> 00:21:01,880
(DOOR CLOSING)

380
00:21:03,440 --> 00:21:04,880
(DOOR LOCKING)

381
00:21:08,240 --> 00:21:09,360
(CROWD MURMURING)

382
00:21:13,000 --> 00:21:15,400
'Tis a thing of beauty indeed.

383
00:21:15,760 --> 00:21:16,760
Hmm!

384
00:21:17,240 --> 00:21:20,040
And will feed a family for a
twelvemonth, when melted down.

385
00:21:20,200 --> 00:21:21,320
Tonight we rest.

386
00:21:21,680 --> 00:21:24,160
Tomorrow we must draw up plans
to rescue Robin.

387
00:21:24,360 --> 00:21:26,360
We shall soon see
how those Mechanicals feel

388
00:21:26,440 --> 00:21:28,480
about the taste of Nottingham steel!

389
00:21:28,960 --> 00:21:30,440
Lord forgive me.

390
00:21:30,880 --> 00:21:32,480
Strange, though, is it not?

391
00:21:32,840 --> 00:21:33,840
What?

392
00:21:34,120 --> 00:21:36,080
All this looting
that the Sheriff is doing.

393
00:21:36,160 --> 00:21:38,760
And yet 'tis only ever gold
that he takes.

394
00:21:39,040 --> 00:21:41,880
Pearls, rubies, all the precious
jewels of the realm

395
00:21:41,960 --> 00:21:44,280
seem no consequence to him.

396
00:21:44,360 --> 00:21:45,520
Only gold.

397
00:21:49,960 --> 00:21:52,520
# Poor Robin and the stranger lay

398
00:21:52,680 --> 00:21:55,040
# In the dungeon all the live-long day

399
00:21:55,720 --> 00:21:58,240
# The Merry Men might pine away

400
00:21:58,680 --> 00:22:00,800
# Upon a Sherwood morning #

401
00:22:00,920 --> 00:22:02,600
(GROANING)

402
00:22:24,280 --> 00:22:26,920
Eat, my lady, eat. Hmm?

403
00:22:28,080 --> 00:22:31,400
Let it not be said that the Sheriff
of Nottingham is a poor host.

404
00:22:31,800 --> 00:22:33,600
I had a bag of crisps
this morning, thanks.

405
00:22:33,840 --> 00:22:36,080
Your words are strange, fair one.

406
00:22:36,160 --> 00:22:38,040
Hmm, I should think they are.

407
00:22:38,280 --> 00:22:41,280
But I like you. You're refreshingly...

408
00:22:42,080 --> 00:22:43,160
direct.

409
00:22:43,240 --> 00:22:45,560
You can take the girl
out of Blackpool...

410
00:22:49,040 --> 00:22:52,400
Taken from your friend's strange tunic,

411
00:22:53,200 --> 00:22:55,800
an intriguing gallimaufry.

412
00:22:56,680 --> 00:23:00,080
Including this wand.

413
00:23:01,480 --> 00:23:03,960
Evidently a thing of awesome power.

414
00:23:06,480 --> 00:23:07,680
Tell me,

415
00:23:08,680 --> 00:23:10,600
are you from beyond the stars?

416
00:23:10,960 --> 00:23:13,280
You're the one with the robot army,
you tell me.

417
00:23:16,280 --> 00:23:18,000
-I'm sorry?
-No.

418
00:23:18,600 --> 00:23:23,600
Beat your breast, moan, groan as though
20 devils possessed your guts.

419
00:23:23,680 --> 00:23:24,720
What for?

420
00:23:24,800 --> 00:23:27,080
So as to attract the attention
of that gargoyle-faced guard.

421
00:23:28,120 --> 00:23:29,880
It's your plan, you moan.

422
00:23:30,240 --> 00:23:34,200
-No, no, no, it won't work.
-Why?

423
00:23:34,520 --> 00:23:37,400
Uh, because you're clearly
more advanced in years

424
00:23:37,480 --> 00:23:39,200
and you have a sickly aspect to you.

425
00:23:39,280 --> 00:23:40,320
I have a what?

426
00:23:40,680 --> 00:23:42,080
You're as pale as milk.

427
00:23:42,480 --> 00:23:44,560
It's the way with Scots,
they're strangers to vegetables.

428
00:23:44,640 --> 00:23:46,120
I'm not moaning. You moan.

429
00:23:47,080 --> 00:23:49,320
Fine. If you want something doing...

430
00:23:49,560 --> 00:23:52,000
(GROANING LOUDLY)

431
00:23:52,880 --> 00:23:55,080
-Can I rely upon you to do the rest?
-Yes, yes, I know the drill.

432
00:23:56,000 --> 00:23:57,120
What is this din?

433
00:23:57,200 --> 00:23:59,080
No business of yours, cur!

434
00:23:59,360 --> 00:24:01,280
Speak up! I can't hear you.

435
00:24:01,480 --> 00:24:03,480
-What ails him?
-None of your business.

436
00:24:03,560 --> 00:24:04,960
(GROANING CONTINUES)

437
00:24:05,320 --> 00:24:07,120
I said, what ails him?

438
00:24:07,240 --> 00:24:10,800
Well, if you must know,
he's having a nervous breakdown.

439
00:24:11,080 --> 00:24:12,080
A what?

440
00:24:12,160 --> 00:24:15,200
He's like this
whenever he's in any kind of danger.

441
00:24:15,640 --> 00:24:18,200
He just can't seem to cope,
he gets so afraid.

442
00:24:18,320 --> 00:24:19,720
He goes into a kind of fit.

443
00:24:19,800 --> 00:24:23,120
I honestly believe that he may die
of sheer fright

444
00:24:23,200 --> 00:24:26,560
like some tiny, shivering little mouse.

445
00:24:26,640 --> 00:24:27,640
(GROANING)

446
00:24:27,840 --> 00:24:29,080
Oh, God, I think he's soiled himself.

447
00:24:29,160 --> 00:24:32,280
Let him die. It'll save us
the trouble of executing him.

448
00:24:32,480 --> 00:24:33,960
And what will happen to the reward?

449
00:24:34,040 --> 00:24:35,440
(MOANING)

450
00:24:35,520 --> 00:24:36,520
Reward?

451
00:24:36,600 --> 00:24:38,200
DOCTOR: Oh, God,
I shouldn't have said that.

452
00:24:38,280 --> 00:24:39,760
Tell me!

453
00:24:40,800 --> 00:24:42,720
He carries a vital message.

454
00:24:42,800 --> 00:24:44,720
The Prince has promised a bounty!

455
00:24:45,680 --> 00:24:47,920
-A big one?
-An enormous one.

456
00:24:48,680 --> 00:24:49,840
What's that?

457
00:24:50,680 --> 00:24:51,680
Say again?

458
00:24:52,000 --> 00:24:53,920
(FAINTLY) Come close, come close.

459
00:24:57,000 --> 00:24:59,680
Your breath stinks like a serpent,
has anyone ever told you that?

460
00:24:59,760 --> 00:25:00,760
(GRUNTS)

461
00:25:04,640 --> 00:25:05,960
Soiled myself!

462
00:25:06,040 --> 00:25:07,960
Did you? That's getting into character.

463
00:25:08,360 --> 00:25:09,600
Okay, keys!

464
00:25:09,680 --> 00:25:11,000
-I'll get them.
-No, no. I'll get them.

465
00:25:11,080 --> 00:25:12,280
-I will get them
-I'll get them.

466
00:25:12,360 --> 00:25:13,760
-I've got them!
-I'm fine. No, no worries!

467
00:25:13,840 --> 00:25:15,440
-I've got them!
-I'll get...

468
00:25:15,520 --> 00:25:17,440
-Ah!
-(KEYS CLANGING)

469
00:25:19,560 --> 00:25:20,840
(KEYS SPLASHING IN WATER)

470
00:25:22,800 --> 00:25:25,720
-Well, there is a bright side.
-Which is?

471
00:25:26,120 --> 00:25:28,200
Clara didn't see that.

472
00:25:28,520 --> 00:25:29,520
(SIGHS)

473
00:25:29,920 --> 00:25:33,960
But enough of tawdry matters.

474
00:25:36,480 --> 00:25:39,320
Let us talk of softer,

475
00:25:40,800 --> 00:25:41,800
sweeter things.

476
00:25:41,960 --> 00:25:45,200
Ah! Good, yes, I was hoping
we'd get round to that.

477
00:25:45,400 --> 00:25:46,920
-You were?
-Mmm.

478
00:25:47,240 --> 00:25:49,960
For I have known
I was destined to draw the eye

479
00:25:50,040 --> 00:25:53,680
of a great and powerful man
for a long time,

480
00:25:53,760 --> 00:25:57,280
ever since I saw those mysterious
lights in the sky.

481
00:25:57,400 --> 00:25:58,480
You saw them, too?

482
00:25:58,560 --> 00:26:02,160
And those strange mechanical men,
with their promises.

483
00:26:04,640 --> 00:26:07,320
-1, too, have experienced this.
-Really?

484
00:26:07,440 --> 00:26:09,640
Well, I would never have guessed.
Tell me your story.

485
00:26:10,000 --> 00:26:11,840
-Tell me yours.
-Oh, no, no, no.

486
00:26:11,920 --> 00:26:13,320
But you have to go first.

487
00:26:13,400 --> 00:26:14,400
Why so?

488
00:26:16,800 --> 00:26:20,000
Because great men always precede.

489
00:26:21,760 --> 00:26:22,760
You have a point.

490
00:26:23,280 --> 00:26:24,440
Your story, then.

491
00:26:25,920 --> 00:26:28,520
Once upon a time, there was a brave

492
00:26:29,680 --> 00:26:33,320
and clever and handsome man...

493
00:26:33,920 --> 00:26:35,840
I can almost picture him.

494
00:26:36,400 --> 00:26:37,880
I don't even have to close my eyes.

495
00:26:38,240 --> 00:26:41,120
...unappreciated by his royal master.

496
00:26:41,360 --> 00:26:42,360
Prince John?

497
00:26:42,560 --> 00:26:43,880
The very same.

498
00:26:44,600 --> 00:26:49,360
Then came the lights in the sky
and everything changed?

499
00:26:50,040 --> 00:26:52,440
The sky ship came to Earth

500
00:26:52,800 --> 00:26:55,600
in a fury of fire!

501
00:26:55,680 --> 00:26:58,720
I'd almost call it a crash.
I remember it well.

502
00:26:58,840 --> 00:27:01,480
A craft from the heavenly spheres,
bedight with twinkling lights

503
00:27:01,560 --> 00:27:03,800
and miracles beyond imagining!

504
00:27:04,200 --> 00:27:07,120
The most beautiful thing the brave

505
00:27:07,840 --> 00:27:10,560
and handsome man had ever seen.

506
00:27:10,800 --> 00:27:14,840
And I suppose the mechanical men
saw you as their natural leader?

507
00:27:15,680 --> 00:27:17,920
It wasl and I alone

508
00:27:18,640 --> 00:27:22,080
to whom the mechanical men
within imparted their secrets.

509
00:27:22,520 --> 00:27:25,240
Shortly, I shall be the most
powerful man in the realm.

510
00:27:25,920 --> 00:27:28,480
King in all but name,

511
00:27:28,560 --> 00:27:30,840
for Nottingham is not enough.

512
00:27:31,040 --> 00:27:33,040
-It isn't?
-After this...

513
00:27:33,880 --> 00:27:35,920
-Derby!
-Right.

514
00:27:36,000 --> 00:27:37,000
Then...

515
00:27:38,160 --> 00:27:39,160
Lincoln.

516
00:27:39,680 --> 00:27:41,800
-And after Lincoln...
-Worksop?

517
00:27:43,200 --> 00:27:44,720
The world!

518
00:27:50,680 --> 00:27:53,120
-Now what?
-First, a blacksmith's forge.

519
00:27:53,320 --> 00:27:55,320
So as to remove our chains? (GRUNTS)

520
00:27:55,520 --> 00:27:56,640
No.

521
00:27:57,120 --> 00:27:59,320
So I can knock up
an ornamental plant stand.

522
00:27:59,960 --> 00:28:01,840
Of course it's so we can get rid
of our chains!

523
00:28:01,920 --> 00:28:03,360
I don't want to be manacled
to you all night.

524
00:28:03,440 --> 00:28:04,520
(LAUGHING)

525
00:28:04,600 --> 00:28:06,480
Oh, no, please. Please, don't do that!

526
00:28:06,560 --> 00:28:09,080
-"Ornamental plant stand".
-It's not even that funny!

527
00:28:09,160 --> 00:28:13,000
-You're an amusing fellow, Doctor!
-Oh, don't! Can you just stop?

528
00:28:13,080 --> 00:28:14,280
(CONTINUES LAUGHING)

529
00:28:14,360 --> 00:28:15,920
You'll give yourself a hernia!

530
00:28:17,280 --> 00:28:20,640
So what are you hanging around here for,
then, Your Majesty?

531
00:28:21,400 --> 00:28:23,280
Why are you bothering to squeeze
pips out of peasants

532
00:28:23,360 --> 00:28:24,640
if you've got a sky ship on standby?

533
00:28:24,720 --> 00:28:25,800
Enough questions.

534
00:28:27,680 --> 00:28:29,960
I'm impatient to hear your story.

535
00:28:30,400 --> 00:28:34,160
Oh, but I do not have one.

536
00:28:34,320 --> 00:28:36,280
I was lying.

537
00:28:36,360 --> 00:28:38,000
-Lying?
-Yeah.

538
00:28:38,080 --> 00:28:39,920
People are so much better
at sharing information

539
00:28:40,000 --> 00:28:42,680
if they think the other person
has already got it.

540
00:28:44,560 --> 00:28:46,960
-Oh, that's very clever.
-Thank you.

541
00:28:48,520 --> 00:28:49,960
You'll do very well.

542
00:28:51,360 --> 00:28:52,360
For what?

543
00:28:53,720 --> 00:28:55,000
Doesn't every king

544
00:28:56,680 --> 00:28:58,360
require a consort?

545
00:28:59,480 --> 00:29:02,800
Right, you do that again
and you'll regret that.

546
00:29:18,960 --> 00:29:22,320
At last, something real.
No more fairy tales.

547
00:29:24,640 --> 00:29:25,840
What is this place?

548
00:29:25,920 --> 00:29:28,160
A spaceship.
More 29th century than 12th.

549
00:29:28,240 --> 00:29:32,240
Data banks, data banks, data banks!
Where was this ship headed?

550
00:29:37,680 --> 00:29:39,520
The Promised Land again.

551
00:29:40,200 --> 00:29:42,480
Like the Half-Face Man
but more sophisticated.

552
00:29:43,680 --> 00:29:47,000
It disguised itself
as a 12th-century castle,

553
00:29:47,560 --> 00:29:51,720
emerges into the culture,
tries to keep a low profile,

554
00:29:52,040 --> 00:29:53,840
so no one notices.

555
00:29:54,000 --> 00:29:55,920
That explains the robot knights.

556
00:29:56,360 --> 00:29:59,600
But the engines...
The engines are damaged.

557
00:30:00,040 --> 00:30:02,960
They're leaking radiation
into the local atmosphere,

558
00:30:03,320 --> 00:30:06,360
creating a temporary climate
of staggering benevolence.

559
00:30:06,600 --> 00:30:08,520
- I beg pardon?
-Told you.

560
00:30:08,720 --> 00:30:09,920
It's too sunny.

561
00:30:10,560 --> 00:30:11,920
It's too green.

562
00:30:12,040 --> 00:30:15,960
And there is even an evil sheriff
to oppress the locals.

563
00:30:16,360 --> 00:30:19,080
-This explains everything, even you.
-It does?

564
00:30:19,160 --> 00:30:21,640
Well, what does every oppressed
peasant workforce need?

565
00:30:21,760 --> 00:30:24,080
The illusion of hope.

566
00:30:24,240 --> 00:30:27,240
Some silly story to get them
through the day,

567
00:30:27,400 --> 00:30:30,080
lull them into docility
and keep them working.

568
00:30:30,440 --> 00:30:32,120
Ship's data banks.

569
00:30:32,840 --> 00:30:35,880
Full of every myth and legend
you could hope for, including...

570
00:30:37,160 --> 00:30:38,520
Robin Hood.

571
00:30:38,720 --> 00:30:39,760
(COMPUTER BEEPS)

572
00:30:43,600 --> 00:30:46,600
Isn't it time you came clean with me?

573
00:30:52,640 --> 00:30:54,080
You're not real and you know it!

574
00:30:54,160 --> 00:30:56,720
Look at you, perfect eyes,
perfect teeth.

575
00:30:56,800 --> 00:30:59,360
Nobody has a jawline like that!

576
00:30:59,480 --> 00:31:01,760
You're as much a part of what is
happening here as the Sheriff

577
00:31:01,840 --> 00:31:05,040
and his metal knights. You're a robot.

578
00:31:05,280 --> 00:31:09,960
You dare to accuse me of collusion
with that villain, the Sheriff?

579
00:31:10,040 --> 00:31:12,560
-I dare!
-You false-tongued knave!

580
00:31:12,640 --> 00:31:15,440
I should have skewered you
when I had the chance!

581
00:31:15,520 --> 00:31:17,200
I would like to see you try!

582
00:31:17,280 --> 00:31:18,280
(ENGINE POWERING UP)

583
00:31:22,680 --> 00:31:24,520
Oh, yeah, yeah, yeah, yeah!

584
00:31:24,600 --> 00:31:26,760
-Surrender, outlaw!
-Very good.

585
00:31:26,880 --> 00:31:28,120
Kill him. Kill Robin Hood!

586
00:31:28,200 --> 00:31:30,040
You can drop
all that stuff now, Sheriff.

587
00:31:30,160 --> 00:31:31,600
-Doctor?
-He is not what you think he is.

588
00:31:31,680 --> 00:31:33,240
This is all play-acting.

589
00:31:33,800 --> 00:31:35,240
We can't just let them kill him!

590
00:31:35,560 --> 00:31:37,280
DOCTOR: You're not fooling
anyone, Sheriff.

591
00:31:37,760 --> 00:31:38,760
(SCREAMING)

592
00:31:43,400 --> 00:31:44,640
What the hell are you doing?

593
00:31:44,720 --> 00:31:46,600
-Surviving.
-No!

594
00:31:46,680 --> 00:31:48,320
No! Clara!

595
00:31:58,720 --> 00:32:01,080
Yeah, sorry about the girl,
such a pretty thing.

596
00:32:01,680 --> 00:32:03,800
What a queen she would have made.

597
00:32:18,080 --> 00:32:19,400
Stop pretending.

598
00:32:19,880 --> 00:32:22,160
You and your fancy robots.

599
00:32:22,240 --> 00:32:24,000
I get it, I understand.

600
00:32:24,160 --> 00:32:26,040
Oh, so you too know my plans?

601
00:32:26,120 --> 00:32:27,280
You and your robots

602
00:32:27,360 --> 00:32:30,360
plundering the surrounding
countryside for all it's worth.

603
00:32:33,040 --> 00:32:34,440
Gold.

604
00:32:34,960 --> 00:32:37,080
Gold! Of course!

605
00:32:37,560 --> 00:32:41,880
Gold! You are creating a matrix of
gold to repair the engine circuitry.

606
00:32:41,960 --> 00:32:44,440
This is the scheme
the Mechanicals have devised.

607
00:32:44,520 --> 00:32:48,440
Soon this sky ship will depart.
Destination, London.

608
00:32:48,520 --> 00:32:50,920
There, I will obliterate the King

609
00:32:51,000 --> 00:32:56,240
and take my rightful place
as ruler of this sceptred isle!

610
00:32:56,760 --> 00:32:59,040
It won't work. There's not a chance.
I've seen the instruments.

611
00:32:59,120 --> 00:33:00,160
There's been too much damage.

612
00:33:00,240 --> 00:33:02,680
You are stoking up a gigantic bomb!

613
00:33:04,920 --> 00:33:05,920
(CLANGING)

614
00:33:07,280 --> 00:33:10,720
COMPUTER: Engine capacity at 48%.

615
00:33:10,920 --> 00:33:12,000
(MEN GROANING)

616
00:33:12,760 --> 00:33:16,040
Engine capacity at 48%.

617
00:33:16,480 --> 00:33:19,840
It's not enough. That's not enough.
It'll never make orbit.

618
00:33:20,920 --> 00:33:21,920
(EXPLOSION)

619
00:33:24,000 --> 00:33:26,920
That's the engines, building in power.

620
00:33:27,240 --> 00:33:29,400
Stupid, stupid Sheriff!

621
00:33:30,080 --> 00:33:34,680
Agh! Go on, give...
Give, you stupid things!

622
00:33:37,280 --> 00:33:38,520
What are you looking at?

623
00:33:47,120 --> 00:33:48,160
Hi.

624
00:33:48,400 --> 00:33:50,360
The time for games is over.

625
00:33:52,600 --> 00:33:53,840
I think I understand you.

626
00:33:53,920 --> 00:33:56,200
The Sheriff's using the gold
to replace something?

627
00:33:56,280 --> 00:33:57,920
That's the principle.

628
00:33:58,200 --> 00:34:00,880
But he's a moron.
If he tries to fly his ship,

629
00:34:00,960 --> 00:34:03,160
it'll explode and wipe out
half the country.

630
00:34:05,400 --> 00:34:08,800
What we need is a little riot.

631
00:34:09,800 --> 00:34:12,560
Time to reflect on lasers and gold.

632
00:34:12,920 --> 00:34:14,920
Spread the word.

633
00:34:15,280 --> 00:34:17,640
You will tell me everything
this Doctor knows

634
00:34:17,720 --> 00:34:20,920
about Robin Hood and his Merry Men.

635
00:34:22,880 --> 00:34:25,000
What is this?
Why are you interrogating me?

636
00:34:25,240 --> 00:34:29,480
And then, you will tell me
exactly who this Doctor is

637
00:34:29,600 --> 00:34:31,880
and what are his plans.

638
00:34:35,000 --> 00:34:37,000
ROBOT: You are fit for lab our.

639
00:34:37,080 --> 00:34:40,600
Stand aside while this peasant unit
ls freed.

640
00:34:40,680 --> 00:34:42,080
I'm afraid you're a little late.

641
00:34:42,160 --> 00:34:43,520
Explain.

642
00:34:43,760 --> 00:34:45,240
I'm already free!

643
00:35:04,360 --> 00:35:05,720
Mine!

644
00:35:06,120 --> 00:35:07,280
Mine.

645
00:35:08,600 --> 00:35:09,640
Mine.

646
00:35:09,720 --> 00:35:13,120
COMPUTER: Engine capacity at 75%.

647
00:35:13,320 --> 00:35:14,440
(BEEPING)

648
00:35:18,320 --> 00:35:19,320
What?

649
00:35:20,080 --> 00:35:24,320
Who will rid me
of this turbulent Doctor?

650
00:35:27,680 --> 00:35:28,680
Come.

651
00:35:29,320 --> 00:35:30,360
(SCREAMING)

652
00:35:34,960 --> 00:35:35,960
(WOMAN SCREAMING)

653
00:35:37,840 --> 00:35:38,960
Ahhh!

654
00:35:39,880 --> 00:35:41,760
Everyone, the last one!

655
00:35:55,400 --> 00:35:58,160
Out, out, out!
Everyone, quickly, get out!

656
00:35:59,680 --> 00:36:00,680
DOCTOR: Quickly!

657
00:36:01,160 --> 00:36:03,080
You've saved us all, clever one.

658
00:36:03,680 --> 00:36:04,680
Thank you.

659
00:36:08,280 --> 00:36:11,600
COMPUTER: Engine capacity at 82%.

660
00:36:11,680 --> 00:36:16,080
You are indeed
an ingenious fellow, Doctor.

661
00:36:16,400 --> 00:36:20,560
But do you really think
your peasants revolt can stop me?

662
00:36:20,760 --> 00:36:23,360
I rather think
you're the revolting one around here.

663
00:36:23,560 --> 00:36:25,400
Bantering, I'm bantering. Listen to me!

664
00:36:25,680 --> 00:36:29,000
You don't have enough gold content
to seal the engine breach.

665
00:36:29,080 --> 00:36:31,480
If you try and take off,
you'll wipe out half of England.

666
00:36:31,560 --> 00:36:32,800
Liar!

667
00:36:33,200 --> 00:36:36,160
From my sky vessel,
I shall rule omnipotent.

668
00:36:36,240 --> 00:36:39,160
You pudding-headed primitive,
shut down the engines.

669
00:36:39,240 --> 00:36:42,160
What you're doing
will alter the course of history.

670
00:36:42,520 --> 00:36:44,080
I sincerely hope so

671
00:36:45,320 --> 00:36:46,920
or I wouldn't be bothering.

672
00:36:49,440 --> 00:36:51,560
Listen to me!
It doesn't have to end like this.

673
00:36:51,640 --> 00:36:54,280
Shut it all down, return Clara to me
and I'll do what I can.

674
00:36:54,360 --> 00:36:55,440
I don't have Clara.

675
00:36:55,560 --> 00:36:56,760
Robin's one of yours!

676
00:36:58,280 --> 00:36:59,360
What did you say?

677
00:36:59,440 --> 00:37:02,200
He's one of your tin-headed puppets,
just like these brutes here.

678
00:37:02,280 --> 00:37:04,960
Robin Hood is not one of mine.

679
00:37:05,120 --> 00:37:09,040
Of course he is. He's a robot,
created by your mechanical mates.

680
00:37:09,120 --> 00:37:10,160
Why would they do that?

681
00:37:10,240 --> 00:37:12,440
To pacify the locals,
give them false hope.

682
00:37:12,520 --> 00:37:14,560
He's the opiate of the masses.

683
00:37:14,760 --> 00:37:17,000
Why would we create an enemy
to fight us?

684
00:37:17,440 --> 00:37:20,200
What sense would that make?
That would be a terrible idea.

685
00:37:20,280 --> 00:37:23,000
Yes! Yes, it would!

686
00:37:23,960 --> 00:37:26,560
Wouldn't it?
Yes, that would be a rubbish idea.

687
00:37:26,800 --> 00:37:28,040
Why would you do that?

688
00:37:28,600 --> 00:37:31,280
But he can't be... He's not real.

689
00:37:31,840 --> 00:37:33,240
He's a legend!

690
00:37:33,680 --> 00:37:34,800
Too kind!

691
00:37:35,600 --> 00:37:38,720
And this legend does not come alone.

692
00:37:39,320 --> 00:37:40,320
Hiya!

693
00:37:50,040 --> 00:37:51,040
-You all right?
-Hell, yeah.

694
00:37:51,120 --> 00:37:52,360
Good!

695
00:37:53,680 --> 00:37:54,800
ROBIN: My men have taken the castle.

696
00:37:54,880 --> 00:37:56,760
-No!
-ROBIN: Now I am going to take you.

697
00:37:56,840 --> 00:37:58,480
This one's all mine!

698
00:37:59,040 --> 00:38:00,040
(ROBOTS POWERING DOWN)

699
00:38:00,400 --> 00:38:03,320
What do you say, outlaw?
A final reckoning?

700
00:38:03,680 --> 00:38:05,000
Oh, yes.

701
00:38:07,960 --> 00:38:09,600
-Are you okay?
-Fine, yeah.

702
00:38:09,680 --> 00:38:10,800
Good. We don't have long.

703
00:38:12,760 --> 00:38:13,800
(GRUNTING)

704
00:38:15,280 --> 00:38:17,520
I shall avenge every slight, outlaw!

705
00:38:17,600 --> 00:38:19,080
-Doctor...
-I know. The whole castle's

706
00:38:19,160 --> 00:38:20,160
about to blow.

707
00:38:20,480 --> 00:38:24,320
You have long been a thorn in my side.

708
00:38:26,040 --> 00:38:29,600
Well, everyone should have a hobby.
Mine's annoying you.

709
00:38:29,680 --> 00:38:32,360
I'll have you boiled in oil
at the castle by sunset.

710
00:38:32,440 --> 00:38:35,800
Can we make it a little earlier?
'Cause that's a little past my bedtime!

711
00:38:42,120 --> 00:38:43,880
I'm too much for you, outlaw!

712
00:38:43,960 --> 00:38:47,440
The first of a new breed.
Half man, half engine!

713
00:38:51,560 --> 00:38:52,920
Never ageing...

714
00:38:54,760 --> 00:38:55,920
Never tiring...

715
00:39:00,480 --> 00:39:02,000
Are you still talking?

716
00:39:19,120 --> 00:39:23,480
Bow down before your new king,
you prince of knaves!

717
00:39:28,680 --> 00:39:30,760
(SCREAMING)

718
00:39:32,400 --> 00:39:33,400
(SPLASHING)

719
00:39:40,960 --> 00:39:42,000
(SIGHS)

720
00:39:42,080 --> 00:39:44,440
Sorry. Was that...
Was that showing off?

721
00:39:44,520 --> 00:39:45,720
-That was amazing!
-(EXPLOSION)

722
00:39:48,320 --> 00:39:50,320
Run! Come on, run!

723
00:39:58,880 --> 00:40:00,480
(EXPLOSION)

724
00:40:06,360 --> 00:40:07,600
It's never going to make it.

725
00:40:07,680 --> 00:40:09,640
Not enough gold.
It'll never make it into orbit.

726
00:40:09,720 --> 00:40:11,600
-Where is it? Where did it go?
-Where did what go?

727
00:40:11,680 --> 00:40:13,600
-The golden arrow!
-Tuck!

728
00:40:14,480 --> 00:40:16,920
-You took it?
-Of course we did. We're robbers.

729
00:40:17,000 --> 00:40:18,040
I love you boys!

730
00:40:18,120 --> 00:40:19,480
CLARA: Doctor, what are you suggesting?

731
00:40:19,560 --> 00:40:20,800
Golden arrow.

732
00:40:21,120 --> 00:40:24,320
It might just be enough gold content
to get the ship into orbit

733
00:40:24,400 --> 00:40:25,960
and out of harm's way.

734
00:40:27,240 --> 00:40:30,360
Well, it has to be you.
My arm is injured.

735
00:40:34,920 --> 00:40:37,560
You're good at this! I saw you!
You won the tournament!

736
00:40:37,640 --> 00:40:38,640
I cheated.

737
00:40:38,800 --> 00:40:40,560
I made a special arrow
with a homing device.

738
00:40:40,640 --> 00:40:42,200
Oh, brilliant! Right, let me have a go.

739
00:40:42,280 --> 00:40:44,800
You? You do tae Kwon do!
That's not the same thing as this!

740
00:40:44,880 --> 00:40:47,480
My friends.
Surely, we can manage it together?

741
00:40:50,680 --> 00:40:54,000
COMPUTER: Engine capacity at 83%.

742
00:40:54,080 --> 00:40:56,960
ROBOT: Insufficient power to achieve
escape velocity.

743
00:41:06,800 --> 00:41:08,320
Maximum power surge.

744
00:41:16,200 --> 00:41:19,480
COMPUTER: Engines critical.
Engines critical.

745
00:41:19,880 --> 00:41:20,880
Engines crit...

746
00:41:23,160 --> 00:41:24,200
(CHEERING)

747
00:41:25,680 --> 00:41:28,640
# One awful day in Nottingham

748
00:41:28,720 --> 00:41:31,320
# Brave Robin Hood was in a jam

749
00:41:31,480 --> 00:41:34,240
# The arrow flew with true... #

750
00:41:34,320 --> 00:41:35,880
Give it a rest, Alan.

751
00:41:36,320 --> 00:41:37,400
Give me my lute!

752
00:41:37,800 --> 00:41:39,160
(ALL LAUGHING)

753
00:41:39,280 --> 00:41:41,160
Still not keen on the laughing thing?

754
00:41:41,280 --> 00:41:44,480
-No, no, no, no.
- (GIGGLES)

755
00:41:49,080 --> 00:41:50,080
Whoo-hoo!

756
00:41:53,120 --> 00:41:54,120
Ah!

757
00:41:54,600 --> 00:41:56,560
I am going to miss you.

758
00:41:57,600 --> 00:41:59,720
-You're very naughty.
-Oh, I know.

759
00:42:02,440 --> 00:42:04,160
Whoever he is...

760
00:42:06,440 --> 00:42:08,320
he is a very lucky man.

761
00:42:09,240 --> 00:42:10,880
Marian is very lucky, too.

762
00:42:13,640 --> 00:42:15,640
- I fear not.
-Don't give up.

763
00:42:17,680 --> 00:42:20,400
Not ever, not for one single day.

764
00:42:23,040 --> 00:42:24,720
Be safe, if you can be.

765
00:42:24,960 --> 00:42:27,720
But always be amazing.

766
00:42:28,280 --> 00:42:29,600
Hmm!

767
00:42:32,280 --> 00:42:35,520
Goodbye, Robin Hood.

768
00:42:35,880 --> 00:42:38,720
Goodbye, Clara Oswald.

769
00:42:51,440 --> 00:42:55,120
So, is it true, Doctor?

770
00:42:55,560 --> 00:42:56,760
Is what true?

771
00:42:56,920 --> 00:42:59,160
That in the future
I am forgotten as a real man?

772
00:42:59,240 --> 00:43:01,160
I am but a legend?

773
00:43:02,480 --> 00:43:03,760
I'm afraid it is.

774
00:43:04,280 --> 00:43:05,280
Hmm.

775
00:43:07,200 --> 00:43:09,600
Good. History is a burden.

776
00:43:10,640 --> 00:43:12,720
Stories can make us fly.

777
00:43:13,480 --> 00:43:16,040
I'm still having a little trouble
believing yours, I'm afraid.

778
00:43:16,160 --> 00:43:17,480
Is it so hard to credit?

779
00:43:18,520 --> 00:43:20,040
That a man born into wealth
and privilege

780
00:43:20,120 --> 00:43:22,840
should find the plight of the oppressed
and weak too much to bear?

781
00:43:22,920 --> 00:43:24,040
-No...
-Until one night,

782
00:43:24,120 --> 00:43:26,120
he is moved to steal a Tardis?

783
00:43:28,000 --> 00:43:30,680
Fly among the stars,
fighting the good fight?

784
00:43:31,400 --> 00:43:33,280
Clara told me your stories.

785
00:43:33,600 --> 00:43:36,080
She should not have told you
any of that.

786
00:43:36,160 --> 00:43:37,280
Well...

787
00:43:37,360 --> 00:43:40,880
Well, once the story started,
she could hardly stop herself.

788
00:43:42,320 --> 00:43:44,200
You are her hero, I think.

789
00:43:44,280 --> 00:43:45,440
I'm not a hero.

790
00:43:46,040 --> 00:43:48,160
Well, neither am I.

791
00:43:49,960 --> 00:43:52,480
But if we both keep pretending to be...

792
00:43:52,800 --> 00:43:53,800
Ha-ha!

793
00:43:55,800 --> 00:43:58,040
Perhaps others will be
heroes in our name.

794
00:43:58,480 --> 00:44:01,680
Perhaps we will both be stories.

795
00:44:02,120 --> 00:44:04,680
And may those stories never end.

796
00:44:10,040 --> 00:44:13,440
Goodbye, Doctor,
Time Lord of Gallifrey.

797
00:44:13,960 --> 00:44:17,880
Goodbye, Robin Hood, Earl of Loxley.

798
00:44:18,480 --> 00:44:19,880
And remember, Doctor...

799
00:44:21,800 --> 00:44:23,680
I'm just as real as you are.

800
00:44:34,600 --> 00:44:35,920
Admit it.

801
00:44:36,800 --> 00:44:38,200
You like him.

802
00:44:40,680 --> 00:44:42,600
Well, I'm leaving him a present,
aren't I?

803
00:44:49,000 --> 00:44:50,640
(TARDIS WHOOSHING)

804
00:44:56,840 --> 00:44:58,760
Robin?

805
00:44:59,800 --> 00:45:01,320
I've found you at last.

806
00:45:01,400 --> 00:45:03,440
Marian? Marian!

807
00:45:08,000 --> 00:45:09,200
Ah!

808
00:45:10,160 --> 00:45:11,440
Ha-ha-ha!

809
00:45:11,520 --> 00:45:14,240
Thank you! Thank you, Doctor!

810
00:45:16,880 --> 00:45:18,200
Ha-ha-ha!

811
00:45:20,200 --> 00:45:25,440
DOCTOR: What's that in the mirror
or the corner of your eye?

812
00:45:27,120 --> 00:45:29,280
What's that footstep following

813
00:45:31,080 --> 00:45:32,600
but never passing by?

814
00:45:33,880 --> 00:45:35,440
Perhaps they're all just waiting,

815
00:45:36,040 --> 00:45:37,960
perhaps when we're all dead,

816
00:45:38,240 --> 00:45:41,760
out they'll come a-slithering
from underneath the bed.

817
00:45:49,160 --> 00:45:51,960
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

